## Column names are:
##  case cc3 country year systemic_crisis exch_usd domestic_debt_in_default sovereign_external_debt_default gdp_weighted_default inflation_annual_cpi independence currency_crises inflation_crises banking_crisis

Variables i) systemic_crisis : 0 means that no systemic crisis occurred in the year and 1 means that a systemic crisis occurred in the year.

  1. exch_usd : The exchange rate of the country vis-a-vis the USD.

  2. domestic_debt_in_default : 0 means that no sovereign domestic debt default occurred in the year and 1 means that a sovereign domestic debt default occurred in the year.

  3. sovereign_external_debt_default : 0 means that no sovereign external debt default occurred in the year and 1 means that a sovereign external debt default occurred in the year.

  4. gdp_weighted_default : The total debt in default vis-a-vis the GDP.

  5. inflation_annual_cpi : The annual CPI Inflation rate.

  6. independence : 0 means no independence and 1 means independence.

  7. currency_crises : 0 means that no currency crisis occurred in the year and 1 means that a currency crisis occurred in the year.

  8. inflation_crises : 0 means that no inflation crisis occurred in the year and 1 means that an inflation crisis occurred in the year.

  9. banking_crisis : no_crisis means that no banking crisis occurred in the year and crisis means that a banking crisis occurred in the year.

##Type of crises

Systemic Crisis: Systemic crisis is a domino effect in which a financial trouble spreads. between institutions and markets until it affects the whole monetary and financial system with dire global economic consequences.

Currency Crisis: A currency crisis is a situation in which serious doubt exists as to whether a countrys central bank has sufficient foreign exchange reserves to maintain the countrys fixed exchange rate. The crisis is often accompanied by a speculative attack in the foreign exchange market. A currency crisis results from chronic balance of payments deficits, and thus is also called a balance of payments crisis. Often such a crisis culminates in a devaluation of the currency.

Inflation Crisis: Inflation is a quantitative measure of the rate at which the average price level of a basket of selected goods and services in an economy increases over a period of time. It is the constant rise in the general level of prices where a unit of currency buys less than it did in prior periods.

Banking Crisis: A banking crisis is often associated with financial crisis. It refers to a panic or a bank run during which investors sell off assets or withdraw money from savings accounts because they fear that the value of those assets will drop if they remain in a financial institution.

In the dataset, we can observe the number of observations for each country and the proportion of observations in which a systemic crisis occurred. Notably, the count of observations is fairly consistent across most countries, with the exceptions of Egypt and South Africa, which have an unusually high number of observations, exceeding 100.

When examining the count of systemic crises, it becomes apparent that certain countries, such as the Central African Republic, Nigeria, Kenya, and Zimbabwe, consistently experienced systemic crises across a substantial portion of the observations.

The presence of systemic crises in these countries may be attributed to a variety of factors, including economic vulnerabilities, political instability, or external shocks. Further analysis and contextual information would be needed to gain a deeper understanding of why these specific countries faced such challenges over the observed period. Factors such as government policies, economic conditions, geopolitical influences, and historical events could have contributed to the observed systemic crises in these nations.

The primary objective of the plot is twofold: firstly, it seeks to illustrate the occurrence of systemic crises, and secondly, it aims to depict the dynamics of the local currency exchange rates in relation to the timeline of African independence.

However, a notable challenge arises when examining the effects of independence on systemic crises. The reason for this challenge is the limited availability of observations prior to the attainment of independence. As a result, there is insufficient data to draw meaningful conclusions regarding the impact of independence on systemic crises.

Its essential to understand that the occurrence of a systemic crisis is often closely intertwined with significant fluctuations in the local currency exchange rates. A marked depreciation of the local currency can act as a catalyst for the emergence of systemic crises. In this context, the exchange rate becomes a crucial factor that contributes to the likelihood of systemic crises occurring.

In simpler terms, when the local currency experiences a substantial decline in its value, it can trigger economic instability, financial vulnerabilities, and, subsequently, systemic crises. This underscores the importance of monitoring and understanding the dynamics of exchange rates in the context of systemic crisis analysis.

However, due to the data limitations before independence, a comprehensive assessment of how independence specifically impacted these dynamics may be challenging. Nonetheless, analyzing the available data on systemic crises and exchange rate fluctuations can still provide valuable insights into their interplay within the given timeframe.

library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)

tree_model <- rpart(systemic_crisis ~ inflation_annual_cpi+independence+exch_usd, african_data)

pruned_tree_model <- prune(tree_model, cp = 0.04)

# Display the pruned tree's number of leaf nodes
rpart.plot(pruned_tree_model)

The decision tree has identified an exchange rate (exch_rate) threshold at 16 units of the local currency per 1 USD. This threshold is used to separate the data into two groups: one group with exchange rates less than 16 and another group with exchange rates greater than or equal to 16.

Economic Implications: Economically, this threshold implies that the exchange rate value of 16 serves as a critical point for predicting the likelihood of a systemic crisis:

Exchange Rate < 16: When the exchange rate is less than 16, it suggests a higher likelihood of not experiencing a systemic crisis within the dataset. This may indicate a stronger or more stable local currency relative to the USD.

Exchange Rate 16: When the exchange rate is greater than or equal to 16, it suggests a higher likelihood of experiencing a systemic crisis within the dataset. This may indicate a weaker or less stable local currency relative to the USD.

Its pivotal to acknowledge that systemic crises often coincide with significant fluctuations in the inflation rate. A high or rapidly rising inflation rate can serve as a catalyst for systemic crises. Consequently, the inflation rate emerges as a pivotal factor that shapes the likelihood of systemic crises.

In simpler terms, when an economy experiences a substantial inflationary surge, it sets in motion a chain reaction characterized by economic instability, financial vulnerabilities, and the eventual emergence of systemic crises. This underscores the critical importance of closely monitoring and comprehending inflation rate trends within the broader context of systemic crisis analysis.

# Create an empty data frame to store correlation results
cor_lag <- data.frame(matrix(nrow = 10, ncol = 3))

# Loop through column names (assuming these are the column names you want to analyze)
columns_to_analyze <- c("banking_crisis", "currency_crisis", "inflation_crisis")

for (col_name in columns_to_analyze) {
  # Loop through lag periods from 0 to 9
  for (i in 0:9) {
    # Calculate the lagged variable
    ciao <- african_data %>%
      group_by(country) %>%
      mutate(lag_inflation = lag(.data[[col_name]], n = i))
    
    # Calculate and store the correlation
    col_index <- match(col_name, columns_to_analyze)  # Get the column index
    cor_lag[i + 1, col_index] <- cor(ciao$systemic_crisis, ciao$lag_inflation, use = "complete.obs")
  }
}

colnames(cor_lag) <- columns_to_analyze
cor_lag['lag'] <- 0:9
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)

cor_long <- cor_lag %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = -lag, names_to = "Variable", values_to = "Correlation")

ggplot(cor_long, aes(x = lag, y = Correlation, fill = Variable)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(x = "Lag Variable", y = "Correlation") +
  facet_wrap(~ Variable, scales = "free", ncol = 1) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 0:9, labels = 0:9) +  # Set custom breaks and labels
  theme_minimal()

In this graphical representation, each bar signifies the degree of correlation between the variable systemic crisis and observations of different types of crises that occurred at previous time points. By examining this plot, we can discern significant patterns in the temporal relationships between systemic crises and other types of crises.

Firstly, we observe that the lag 4 of currency crises exhibits the highest correlation with systemic crises. This implies that systemic crises tend to be strongly influenced by currency crises that occurred four time periods earlier.

Secondly, the most notable correlation for inflation crises is found at lag 1. This suggests that systemic crises often coincide with or follow closely after inflation crises that occurred just one time period before.

Lastly, when it comes to banking crises, the most substantial correlation is observed at lag 0. This implies an immediate correspondence between systemic crises and banking crises, indicating that these two types of crises tend to occur simultaneously.

In summary, the presented plot illustrates the temporal associations between systemic crises and other crisis types. It reveals that currency crises tend to influence systemic crises with a lag of four periods, inflation crises with a lag of one period, and banking crises exhibit an immediate temporal correspondence with systemic crises.

As observed, the number of occurrences recorded for systemic crises is significantly lower compared to non-crisis events in the dataset. This imbalance in the data distribution can pose challenges when training machine learning classifiers. Classifiers tend to be biased towards the majority class, which, in this case, is the non-crisis category. This imbalance can result in suboptimal model performance and lower accuracy.

To address this issue, an up-sampling method has been employed. Up-sampling aims to balance the class distribution by increasing the number of observations in the minority class, in this case, systemic crises. By doing so, the classifier is provided with a more balanced set of examples from both classes, which can lead to better model generalization and improved predictive accuracy.

library(caret)
library(yardstick)
## 
## Attaching package: 'yardstick'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:caret':
## 
##     precision, recall, sensitivity, specificity
model_names <- c("KNN", "Random Forest", "Naive Bayes", "SVM")
predictions =  list(ypred_knn, ypred_rf, ypred_nb, ypred_svm)

evaluation_table <- function(model_names, predictions, y_test){
 
  num_models <- length(predictions)
  
  Precision <- numeric(num_models)
  Recall <- numeric(num_models)
  F1_Score <- numeric(num_models)
  Accuracy <- numeric(num_models)
  
  for (i in 1:num_models){
  model <- model_names[[i]]
  prediction <- predictions[[i]]
  
  TP <- sum(prediction == 1 & y_test == 1)
  FN <- sum(prediction == 0 & y_test == 1)
  FP <- sum(prediction == 1 & y_test == 0)
  TN <- sum(prediction == 0 & y_test == 0)
  
  Precision[i] <- TP / (TP + FP)
  Recall[i] <- TP / (TP + FN)
  F1_Score[i] <- 2 * (Precision[i] * Recall[i]) / (Precision[i] + Recall[i])
  Accuracy[i] <- (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN)
  
  }
  evaluation_table <- data.frame(
  Model = model_names,
  Precision = Precision,
  Recall = Recall,
  F1_Score = F1_Score,
  Accuracy = Accuracy
)
  return(evaluation_table)
}
eval_table <- evaluation_table(model_names, predictions, y_test)
print(eval_table)
